crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: Multifunctional Linux malware written in Rust, likely a botnet agent or offensive toolset. The binary contains explicit source code references to modules for DDoS attacks (src/floods/floods.rs), process termination (src/killer/killer.rs), anti-analysis/evasion (src/hide/hide.rs), persistence (src/persistence/save.rs), and potential ransomware or resource locking (src/locker/locker.rs). It utilizes the Tokio async runtime for high-performance networking. Concrete malicious behaviors include process cloning (fork), direct execution of shell commands (/bin/sh via execve), process name manipulation (prctl), and extensive system configuration reconnaissance via /etc/hosts, /etc/resolv.conf, and /proc/self/exe. Relevant IOCs include the specific internal Rust path structure and references to flooding and killing modules.
